column3:
These tables include information on new prevention and relief duties owed. Prevention duties include any activities aimed at preventing a household threatened with homelessness within 56 days from becoming homeless. Relief duties are owed to households that are already homeless and require help to secure settled accommodation.

They are not comparable with the homelessness decisions or prevention/relief activity reported prior to April 2018. This is because amendments to legislation, as introduced by the 2017 HRA, have introduced new duties that mean more people will be eligible for assistance out of homelessness from local authorities. 

The national and regional totals in this data include imputed estimates for missing values based on previous submissions. 31 local authorities failed to provide accurate assessments data in 2021-22, estimated to comprise 10.7% of total assessments in England.

The national and regional totals in this data include imputed estimates for missing values based on previous submissions. 32 local authorities failed to provide accurate duty end data in 2021-22, estimated to comprise 9.8% of prevention outcomes and 9.1% of relief outcomes in England.

Main duty describes the duty a local authority has towards an applicant who is unintentionally homeless, eligible for assistance and has priority need. This definition has not been changed by the 2017 HRA. However, these households are now only owed a main duty if they did not secure accommodation in the prevention or relief stage.

The national and regional totals in this data include imputed estimates for missing values based on previous submissions. 36 local authorities failed to provide accurate decisions data in 2021-22, estimated to comprise 12.9% of total decisions in England. Moreover, 36 local authorities failed to provide accurate main duty end data, estimated to comprise 12.4% of main duty outcomes.

Data in each new release is provisional and subject to revision in future quarters. Local authorities may add new cases late or revise previous data submissions where mistakes have been spotted. 
Where revisions to earlier quarters are made, these will be incorporated into the dataset at the end of the financial year.
More information on data quality and limitations can be found in the written statistical release and technical notes:

Other' incorporates other special reasons, alcohol or drug dependency, and the following priority need categories: those vulnerable as a result of a learning difficulty, time spent in care, in custody, in HM forces or as former asylum seeker and those fleeing home because of violence or the threat of violence (other than domestic abuse).

Some local authorities have been reporting households with children as 'vulnerable' priority needs, even though dependent children should take precedence. We have split out these ambiguous cases under 'Vulnerable with children' to minimise the impact on trends - but 'household includes dependent children' figures are likely to be under-reported compared to previous quarters. We are working with authorities to improve their reporting of priority need.
Applicants who are accepted as homeless because of an emergency, for example fire or flood.
Priority need breakdowns suppressed for local authorities with fewer than 5 households owed a main duty, to prevent disclosure
Totals may not equal the sum of components and percentages may not sum to 100% because of rounding.

Totals include estimates for 36 local authorities (Barnsley, Breckland, Brighton and Hove, Bromsgrove, Charnwood, Coventry, Durham, East Riding of Yorkshire, Eastbourne, Enfield, Halton, Haringey, Harrogate, Hinckley and Bosworth, Hounslow, Kensington and Chelsea, Lambeth, Lewes, Lewisham, Preston, Redditch, Ribble Valley, Rother, Rotherham, Rugby, Sandwell, Slough, Somerset West and Taunton, South Holland, South Kesteven, South Tyneside, Stroud, Tower Hamlets, Westminster, Windsor and Maidenhead, and Wyre Forest) who did not provide accurate data for all four quarters but have provided figures in other quarters. These values were used to derive estimates.
